ispecies-inline|Morpho|''Morpho''}}\n*{{LepIndex |id=146132 |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}\n*[http://eol.org/pages/17446/entries/33962580/overview EOL] Taxonomy and images\n*[http://www.butterfliesofamerica.com/L/t/Morpho_a.htm Butterflies of America] Superb collection of scientific specimen photographs. Many of [[Type (biology)|types]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150901084715/http://en.butterflycorner.net/Genus-MORPHO.349.0.html Butterflycorner.net]\n*[http://www.tolweb.org/Morpho/70770 Tree of Life]\n*[http://www.boldsystems.org/views/taxbrowser.php?taxon=morpho Barcode of Life] Includes images\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722073519/http://mph.fbs.osaka-u.ac.jp/~ssc/morpho.html Osaka University] Excellent images of most species.\n*[http://www.pteron-world.com/topics/classfication/nymphalidae/satyrinae/morphini/morphini2.html Pteron] Japanese site. Good images\n* [http://insecta.pro/genus/morpho/ \"Genus ''Morpho''\"]. ''Insecta.pro''.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051030134224/http://www.goliathus.cz/en/museum-morphidae-10.html Morphidae] in [https://web.archive.org/web/20051030132837/http://www.goliathus.cz/en/museum-homepage-0.html online museum] \u2013 including rare gynandomorph of Morphidae\n<!--*[http://www.pteron-world.com/topics/classfication/satyridae/morphinae2.html Pteron Page 1] [http://www.pteron-world.com/topics/classfication/satyridae/morphinae3.html#morpho Pteron Page 2] In Japanese but [[binomial]] names against the excellent photos.-->\n*[http://www.insectcollector.at/morphos.html Insect Collector photo gallery] Excellent images of many species.\n*[https://www.petcarestores.com/blue-morpho-butterfly-facts-fun/ Blue Morpho Butterfly photos] Anatomy of blue morpho butterfly.\n*[http://www.catalogueoflife.org/browse/tree/id/2391861{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Morpho''] [[Catalogue of Life]]\n*[https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/data/hostplants/search/list.dsml?&Familyqtype=starts+with&Family=&PFamilyqtype=starts+with&PFamily=&Genusqtype=starts+with&Genus=Morpho&PGenusqtype=starts+with&PGenus=&Speciesqtype=starts+with&Species=&PSpeciesqtype=starts+with&PSpecies=&Country=&sort=Family \"Lepidoptera Genus: starts with ''Morpho''\"]. ''HOSTS - a Database of the World's Lepidopteran Hostplants''.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151228004750/http://www.patrickblandin.com/fr/zooms/16-le-genre-morpho-et-la-sous-famille-des-morphinae-nymphalidae- Patrick Blandin] in French\n*[http://worldwildlife.org/biomes/tropical-and-subtropical-moist-broadleaf-forests Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests.Ecoregion.Neotropical]\n\n{{Taxonbar |from=Q645804}}\n\n[[Category:Morpho| ]]\n[[Category:Morphinae]]\n[[Category:Nymphalidae of South America]]\n[[Category:Nymphalidae genera]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Johan Christian Fabricius]]\n", "name_user": "2601:587:301:4880:5d0d:6ab3:7dde:1c84", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morpho"}
{"title_page": "Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel", "text_new": "{{Short description|19th-century German classical scholar}}\n[[Image:Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel - Imagines philologorum.jpg|thumb|right|Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel]]\n'''Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8t\u0254\u026af\u0259l|lang}}; September 27, 1820{{snd}}March 8, 1878), German [[classics|classical scholar]], was born at [[Ludwigsburg]] in the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]]. In 1849 he was appointed extraordinary, in 1857 ordinary professor in the [[university of T\u00fcbingen]], which post he held till his death.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=672}}\n\n==Works==\n\nTeuffel's most important work was his ''Geschichte der r\u00f6mischen Litteratur'' (1870); revisions by [[Ludwig Schwabe]], [[Wilhelm Kroll]] and [[Franz Skutsch]] carried this to a 6th\u20137th edition (1913\u20131920).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} An English translation of the 5th edition by [[George Charles Winter Warr]] was published in 1891\u20131892, as ''Teuffel's History of Roman Literature''. The [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' Eleventh Edition]] described Teuffel's history as \"written in an unattractive style\" but \"indispensable to the student\" especially for its \"bibliographical information\",{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=672}} and Warr's translation is described in the 1996 ''[[Oxford Classical Dictionary]]'' as \"still useful on details\".\n\nAfter the death of [[August Pauly]], the editor of the well-known ''[[Pauly-Wissowa|Realencyclop\u00e4die der classischen Altertumswissenschaft]]'', Teuffel, at first assisted by [[Ernst Christian Walz]], undertook the completion of the work, to which he also contributed numerous articles.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=672}}\n\nHe was also the author of \n*\"Prolegomena zur Chronologie der horazischen Geschichte\" (in ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr die Altertumswissenschaft'', 1842)\n*''Charakteristik des Horaz'' (Leipzig, 1842)\n*''Horaz, eine litterar-historische \u00dcbersicht'' (T\u00fcbingen, 1843),\n\nand of editions of \n*''[[The Clouds]]'' of [[Aristophanes]] (1856)\n*''[[The Persians]]'' of [[Aeschylus]] (1866).\n\nHis ''Studien und Charakteristiken'' (1871; 2nd ed., 1889) contain valuable contributions to the history of Greek and Roman literature.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=673}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911 |wstitle=Teuffel, Wilhelm Siegmund |volume=26 |pages=672\u2013673}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |last=Browning |first=Robert |author2=Peta G. Fowler |author3=Don P. Fowler |editor=Simon Hornblower and Antony Spawforth |encyclopedia=[[Oxford Classical Dictionary|The Oxford Classical Dictionary]] |title=Latin literature |edition=3rd edition, revised |year=2003 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19-860641-9 |page=820}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070925014504/http://meta.montclair.edu/ancient/roman/english/secondary/teuffel/ ''History of Roman Literature''] (English translation) at the Montclair Electronic Text Archive\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teuffel, Wilhelm Siegmund}}\n[[Category:1820 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n[[Category:German classical scholars]]\n[[Category:German encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:People from Ludwigsburg]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen faculty]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n\n\n{{germany-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel - Imagines philologorum.jpg|thumb|right|Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel]]\n'''Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8t\u0254\u026af\u0259l|lang}}; September 27, 1820 \u2013 March 8, 1878), German [[classics|classical scholar]], was born at [[Ludwigsburg]] in the [[Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]]. In 1849 he was appointed extraordinary, in 1857 ordinary professor in the [[university of T\u00fcbingen]], which post he held till his death.\n\n==Works==\n\nTeuffel's most important work was his ''Geschichte der r\u00f6mischen Litteratur'' (1870); revisions by [[Ludwig Schwabe]], [[Wilhelm Kroll]] and [[Franz Skutsch]] carried this to a 6th\u20137th edition (1913\u20131920). An English translation of the 5th edition by [[George Charles Winter Warr]] was published in 1891\u20131892, as ''Teuffel's History of Roman Literature''. The [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' Eleventh Edition]] described Teuffel's history as \"written in an unattractive style\" but \"indispensable to the student\" especially for its \"bibliographical information\",{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} and Warr's translation is described in the 1996 ''[[Oxford Classical Dictionary]]'' as \"still useful on details\".\n\nAfter the death of [[August Pauly]], the editor of the well-known ''[[Pauly-Wissowa|Realencyclop\u00e4die der classischen Altertumswissenschaft]]'', Teuffel, at first assisted by [[Ernst Christian Walz]], undertook the completion of the work, to which he also contributed numerous articles.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nHe was also the author of \n*\"Prolegomena zur Chronologie der horazischen Geschichte\" (in ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr die Altertumswissenschaft'', 1842)\n*''Charakteristik des Horaz'' (Leipzig, 1842)\n*''Horaz, eine litterar-historische \u00dcbersicht'' (T\u00fcbingen, 1843),\n\nand of editions of \n*''[[The Clouds]]'' of [[Aristophanes]] (1856)\n*''[[The Persians]]'' of [[Aeschylus]] (1866).\n\nHis ''Studien und Charakteristiken'' (1871; 2nd ed., 1889) contain valuable contributions to the history of Greek and Roman literature.\n\n==Notes==\n{{more footnotes|date=January 2014 }}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911 |wstitle=Teuffel, Wilhelm Siegmund  }}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |last=Browning |first=Robert |author2=Peta G. Fowler |author3=Don P. Fowler |editor=Simon Hornblower and Antony Spawforth |encyclopedia=[[Oxford Classical Dictionary|The Oxford Classical Dictionary]] |title=Latin literature |edition=3rd edition, revised |year=2003 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19-860641-9 |page=820}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Wilhelm Siegmund Teuffel}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070925014504/http://meta.montclair.edu/ancient/roman/english/secondary/teuffel/ ''History of Roman Literature''] (English translation) at the Montclair Electronic Text Archive\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teuffel, Wilhelm Siegmund}}\n[[Category:1820 births]]\n[[Category:1878 deaths]]\n[[Category:German classical scholars]]\n[[Category:German encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:People from Ludwigsburg]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen faculty]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n\n\n{{germany-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DavidBrooks-AWB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix EB1911 attributions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_Siegmund_Teuffel"}
{"title_page": "Fred A. Field", "text_new": "{{Short description|U.S. Marshal for Vermont}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Fred A. Field\n|image        = Fred A. Field (US Marshal for Vermont).jpg\n|caption      = ''The Vermonter'' magazine, August 1897\n|office1      = [[United States Marshal]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Vermont|District of Vermont]]\n|term_start1  = June 14, 1898\n|term_end1    = October 15, 1903\n|predecessor1 = [[Emory S. Harris]]\n|successor1   = Frank H. Chapman\n|office2      = [[Postmaster]] of [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]]\n|term_start2  = 1889\n|term_end2    = 1893\n|predecessor2 = L. W. Redington\n|successor2   = John D. Hanrahan\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1850|06|17}}\n|birth_place  = [[Brandon, Vermont]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1935|04|18|1850|06|17}}\n|death_place  = [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]], U.S.\n|restingplace = Evergreen Cemetery,<br/>Rutland, Vermont\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lillie Clark (m. 1873-1935, his death)\n|children     = 3\n|relatives    = \n|education    = [[Burr and Burton Academy|Burr and Burton Seminary]], [[Manchester, Vermont]]\n|occupation   = Businessman<br/>Government official\n}}\n\n'''Fred A. Field''' (June 17, 1850 - April 18, 1935) was a businessman and public official from Vermont. Among the offices in which he served, Fields was [[United States Marshal]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Vermont|District of Vermont]] from 1898 to 1903.\n\n==Early life==\nFrederick A. Field (usually referred to as Fred A. Field) was born in [[Brandon, Vermont]] on June 17, 1850, a son of Minerva (Davenport) Field and William M. Field, who served as [[sheriff]] of [[Rutland County, Vermont|Rutland County]] and president of the Rutland Savings Bank.{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}} His family moved to [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland]] in 1862 and Field was educated in the schools of Brandon and Rutland, and graduated from [[Burr and Burton Academy|Burr and Burton Seminary]] in [[Manchester, Vermont|Manchester]].{{sfn|\"Honored Vermonters\"}}\n\n==Start of career==\nField began his career as a clerk in the Rutland post office and advanced to become Rutland's assistant postmaster from 1872 to 1884.{{sfn|Dodge}} From 1884 to 1885, he was a [[United States Postal Inspection Service|U.S. postal inspector]], with responsibility for law enforcement and oversight of an eighteen-state district.{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Honored Vermonters\"}} In 1885, he was reappointed Rutland's assistant postmaster, and he served until 1889.{{sfn|\"Rutland's Postmaster\"}}\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Field served Rutland village as a school board member and village trustee.{{sfn|Dodge}} After Rutland was incorporated as a city, he served as its treasurer from 1894 to 1895.{{sfn|Dodge}} He was the chairman of Rutland's Republican committee, and secretary and chairman of the [[Rutland County, Vermont|Rutland County]] committee.{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\nFrom 1888 to 1893, Field served as Rutland's [[postmaster]].{{sfn|Dodge}} In addition to his work for the post office, Field operated an investment brokerage, which dealt in stocks, bonds, and real estate.{{sfn|\"Dealer in Investment Securities\"}}\n\nA longtime civic activist, Fields' professional and fraternal memberships included the board of trustees of the Rutland Savings Bank and the Rutland Board of Trade, of which he was a charter member.{{sfn|Dodge}} Field was also a director of Rutland's People's Gas Light Company, treasurer of Rutland's Evergreen Cemetery, treasurer of the State Mutual Fire Insurance Company, and secretary of the Rutland Improvement League.{{sfn|Dodge}} In addition, he was also a member of the [[Freemasonry|Masons]], [[Knights of Pythias]], and [[Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks|Elks]].{{sfn|Dodge}}\n\n==U.S. Marshal==\nIn 1898, Field was appointed [[United States District Court for the District of Vermont#U.S. Marshals and dates of appointment|U.S. Marshal for Vermont]], succeeding [[Emory S. Harris]].{{sfn|\"Vermont: Fred A. Field\"}} He served until 1903, and was succeeded on a temporary basis by Frank H. Chapman.{{sfn|\"Frank H. Chapman\"}}\n\nField's commission was terminated by President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] on October 15, 1903.{{sfn|\"Removed from Office\"}} The termination resulted from a June 1903 incident in which he was accused of dereliction and neglect after three Chinese prisoners he was transporting effected an escape.{{sfn|\"Removed from Office\"}} Field argued that responsibility rested with the transportation company contracted to deport the prisoners, but when the incident became public knowledge, Field was removed from office.{{sfn|\"Removed from Office\"}}{{sfn|\"U. S. Marshal Field Removed\"}}\n\nAfter Field was removed, Vermont's federal district judge, [[Hoyt Henry Wheeler]] appointed Chapman, then serving as Field's chief deputy, to temporarily fill the vacancy.{{sfn|\"Frank H. Chapman\"}} Chapman acted as marshal for five days, after which [[Horace W. Bailey]] was appointed as Field's permanent replacement.{{sfn|\"Horace W. Bailey\"}} Bailey then reappointed Chapman as chief deputy.{{sfn|\"Horace W. Bailey\"}}\n\n==Later life==\nAfter leaving office, Field was the principal of a Rutland real estate and insurance agency, Fred A. Field & Son.{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}} Despite his advanced age, he remained active in the business until a few weeks before his death.{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}} He maintained an interest in Rutland's civic life; in 1933 he was chairman of a Chamber of Commerce committee that successfully lobbied for construction of new federal building in Rutland.{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}}\n\n==Death and burial==\nField died in Rutland on April 18, 1935.{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}} He was buried at Evergreen Cemetery in Rutland.{{sfn|\"Funeral Held\"}}\n\n==Family==\nIn 1873, Field married Lillie Clark (1854-1942) of Rutland.{{sfn|Dodge}} They were the parents of three sons, Richard, William and Fred Jr.{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n*{{cite book |last=Dodge |first=Prentiss Cutler |date=1912 |title=Encyclopedia of Vermont Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt2_3hTQxFMC&pg=PA188 |location=Burlington, VT |publisher=Ullery Publishing Company |pages=188-189 |via=[[Google Books]] |ref={{sfnRef|Dodge}}}}\n\n===Magazines===\n*{{cite magazine |date=August 1897 |title=Honored Vermonters: Hon. Fred A. Field |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmdEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA14 |magazine=The Vermonter |location=St. Albans, VT |publisher=Charles Spooner Forbes |via=[[Google Books]] |page= |ref={{sfnRef|\"Honored Vermonters\"}}}}\n\n===Newspapers===\n*{{cite news |date=June 26, 1889 |title=Rutland's Postmaster |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48904843/rutlands-postmaster/ |work=[[Rutland Herald]] |location=Rutland, VT |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Rutland's Postmaster\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=June 22, 1898 |title=Vermont: Fred A. Field |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48900589/fred-a-field/ |work=Vermont Watchman and State Journal |location=Montpelier, VT |page=2 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Vermont: Fred A. Field\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=June 23, 1898 |title=Fred A. Field, Dealer in Investment Securities |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48900876/fred-a-field/ |work=[[Manchester Journal]] |location=Manchester, VT |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Dealer in Investment Securities\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=October 15, 1903 |title=Marshal F. A. Field Removed from Office |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901274/removed-from-office/ |work=Barre Daily Times |location=Barre, VT |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Removed from Office\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=October 16, 1903 |title=U. S. Marshal Field Removed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901453/field-removed/ |work=[[Rutland Herald]] |location=Rutland, VT |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"U. S. Marshal Field Removed\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=October 17, 1903 |title=Deputy United States Marshal Frank H. Chapman |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48903530/frank-h-chapman/ |work=[[Rutland Herald]] |location=Rutland, VT |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Frank H. Chapman\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=November 3, 1903 |title=Horace W. Bailey |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48903814/horace-w-bailey/ |work=[[Rutland Herald]] |location=Rutland, VT |page=4 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Horace W. Bailey\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=April 19, 1935 |title=Fred A. Field, Sr., Dies at Age of 84 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48899817/fred-field-dies/ |work=[[Rutland Herald]] |location=Rutland, VT |page=1 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}}}}\n*{{cite news |date=April 22, 1935 |title=Funeral Held for Fred A. Field, Sr. |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48899968/obituary-for-fred-a-field-aged-84/|work=[[Burlington Free Press]] |location=Burlington, VT |page=2 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |ref={{sfnRef|\"Funeral Held\"}}}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Findagrave|70097959}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Field, Fred A.}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Brandon, Vermont]]\n[[Category:People from Rutland (city), Vermont]]\n[[Category:Vermont Republicans]]\n[[Category:American postmasters]]\n[[Category:United States Marshals]]\n[[Category:Burials in Vermont]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|U.S. Marshal for Vermont}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Fred A. Field\n|image        = Fred A. Field (US Marshal for Vermont).jpg\n|caption      = ''The Vermonter'' magazine, August 1897\n|office1      = [[United States Marshal]] for the [[United States District Court for the District of Vermont|District of Vermont]]\n|term_start1  = June 14, 1898\n|term_end1    = October 15, 1903\n|predecessor1 = [[Emory S. Harris]]\n|successor1   = Frank H. Chapman\n|office2      = [[Postmaster]] of [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]]\n|term_start2  = 1889\n|term_end2    = 1893\n|predecessor2 = L. W. Redington\n|successor2   = John D. Hanrahan\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1850|06|17}}\n|birth_place  = [[Brandon, Vermont]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1935|04|18|1850|06|17}}\n|death_place  = [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland, Vermont]], U.S.\n|restingplace = Evergreen Cemetery,<br/>Rutland, Vermont\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Lillie Clark (m. 1873-1935, his death)\n|children     = 3\n|relatives    = \n|education    = [[Burr and Burton Academy|Burr and Burton Seminary]], [[Manchester, Vermont]]\n|occupation   = Businessman<br/>Government official\n}}\n\n'''Fred A. Field''' (June 17, 1850 - April 18, 1935) was a businessman and public official from Vermont. Among the offices in which he served, Fields was Vermont's United States Marshal from 1898 to 1903.\n\n==Early life==\nFrederick A. Field (usually referred to as Fred A. Field) was born in [[Brandon, Vermont]] on June 17, 1850, a son of Minerva (Davenport) Field and William M. Field, who served as [[sheriff]] of [[Rutland County, Vermont|Rutland County]] and president of the Rutland Savings Bank.{{sfn|Dodge}}{{sfn|\"Fred A. Field, Sr.\"}} His family moved to [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland]] in 1862 and Field was educated in the schools of Brandon and Rutland, and graduated from [[Burr and Burton Academy|Burr and Burton Seminary]] in [[Manchester, Vermont|Manchester]].{{sfn|\"Honored Vermonters\"}}\n\n==Start of career==\nField began his career as a clerk in the Rutland post office and advanced to become Rutland's assistant postmaster from 1872 to 1884.{{sfn|Dodge}} From 1884 to 1885, he was a [[United States Postal Inspec